[{"id":30143,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"<p>Match List-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> with List-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>.</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\">List-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\">List-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(a)</td>\t\t\t<td>Siderite</td>\t\t\t<td>(i)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(b)</td>\t\t\t<td>Calamine</td>\t\t\t<td>(ii)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ca</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(c)</td>\t\t\t<td>Malachite</td>\t\t\t<td>(iii)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(d)</td>\t\t\t<td>Cryolite</td>\t\t\t<td>(iv)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>(v)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>Choose the correct answer from the options given below:</p>","question":"<p>Match List-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> with List-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>.</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\">List-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\">List-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(a)</td>\t\t\t<td>Siderite</td>\t\t\t<td>(i)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(b)</td>\t\t\t<td>Calamine</td>\t\t\t<td>(ii)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ca</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(c)</td>\t\t\t<td>Malachite</td>\t\t\t<td>(iii)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(d)</td>\t\t\t<td>Cryolite</td>\t\t\t<td>(iv)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>(v)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>Choose the correct answer from the options given below:</p>","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iv</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iv</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Siderite is a mineral composed of iron (II) carbonate&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.&nbsp;It is a widespread mineral that is an ore of iron.&nbsp;</p><p>Calamine:&nbsp;Zinc ore is most commonly found as zinc carbonate&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ZnCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> known as calamine or smithsonite.&nbsp;</p><p>Malachite <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CuCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msub></math>,&nbsp;&nbsp;Malachite&nbsp;is a copper carbonate hydroxide mineral</p><p>Cryolite&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>AlF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math>, which consists of Aluminium, Sodium &amp; Fluorine.</p>","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a6b417cc3fb48d674ec"},{"id":30136,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"<p>Match list-I with list-II :</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>List-I</td>\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>List-II</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(a)</td>\t\t\t<td>Mercury</td>\t\t\t<td>(i)</td>\t\t\t<td>Vapour phase refining</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(b)</td>\t\t\t<td>Copper</td>\t\t\t<td>(ii)</td>\t\t\t<td>Distillation refining</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(c)</td>\t\t\t<td>Silicon</td>\t\t\t<td>(iii)</td>\t\t\t<td>Electrolytic refining</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(d)</td>\t\t\t<td>Nickel</td>\t\t\t<td>(iv)</td>\t\t\t<td>Zone refining</td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>Choose the most appropriate answer from the option given below:</p>","question":"<p>Match list-I with list-II :</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>List-I</td>\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>List-II</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(a)</td>\t\t\t<td>Mercury</td>\t\t\t<td>(i)</td>\t\t\t<td>Vapour phase refining</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(b)</td>\t\t\t<td>Copper</td>\t\t\t<td>(ii)</td>\t\t\t<td>Distillation refining</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(c)</td>\t\t\t<td>Silicon</td>\t\t\t<td>(iii)</td>\t\t\t<td>Electrolytic refining</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(d)</td>\t\t\t<td>Nickel</td>\t\t\t<td>(iv)</td>\t\t\t<td>Zone refining</td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>Choose the most appropriate answer from the option given below:</p>","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iii</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iv</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"(a) Mercury <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> Distillation refining<br />(b) Copper <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> Electrolytic refining<br />(c) Silicon <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> Zone refining<br />(d) Nickel <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> Vapour phase refining","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a69417cc3fb48d6705a"},{"id":30160,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"The correct statement is:","question":"The correct statement is:","options":["Aniline is a froth stabilizer.","Zone refining process is used for the refining of titanium.","Zincite is a carbonate ore.","Sodium cyanide cannot be used in the metallurgy of silver."],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math> Aniline is the forth stabilizer.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math> Zone refining process is not used for refining of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math> Zincite is <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> Sodium cyanide is used in the metallurgy of silver","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a66417cc3fb48d66665"},{"id":30150,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"Boron and silicon of very high purity can be obtained through :","question":"Boron and silicon of very high purity can be obtained through :","options":["liquation","zone refining","vapour phase refining","electrolytic refining"],"answer":1,"solution":"Germanium, Silicon, Boron, Gallium and Indium can be obtained in pure state by zone refining process.","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 2)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a68417cc3fb48d66b93"},{"id":30121,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"<p>Match List - I with List - II :</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>List-I</strong></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>List-II</strong></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(A)</td>\t\t\t<td>Sphalerite</td>\t\t\t<td>(I)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(B)</td>\t\t\t<td>Calamine</td>\t\t\t<td>(II)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PbS</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(C)</td>\t\t\t<td>Galena</td>\t\t\t<td>(III)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ZnCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(D)</td>\t\t\t<td>Siderite</td>\t\t\t<td>(IV)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ZnS</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>Choose the most appropriate answer from the options given below :</p>","question":"<p>Match List - I with List - II :</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>List-I</strong></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>List-II</strong></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(A)</td>\t\t\t<td>Sphalerite</td>\t\t\t<td>(I)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(B)</td>\t\t\t<td>Calamine</td>\t\t\t<td>(II)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PbS</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(C)</td>\t\t\t<td>Galena</td>\t\t\t<td>(III)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ZnCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(D)</td>\t\t\t<td>Siderite</td>\t\t\t<td>(IV)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ZnS</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>Choose the most appropriate answer from the options given below :</p>","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Calamine is the carbonate ore of zinc.It composition is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ZnCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</p><p>Galena is also called lead glance is the natural mineral form of lead (ii) sulfide,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PbS</mi></math></p><p>Sphalerite is a sulfide mineral with the formula<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ZnS</mi></math>.&nbsp;It is the most important ore of zinc.</p><p>Siderite&nbsp;is a mineral&nbsp;composed of iron(II) carbonate&nbsp;(FeCO<sub>3</sub>).</p>","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a6c417cc3fb48d67757"},{"id":30168,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"In the Hall-Heroult process, aluminium is formed at the cathode. The cathode is made out of:","question":"In the Hall-Heroult process, aluminium is formed at the cathode. The cathode is made out of:","options":["Platinum","Carbon","Copper","Pure aluminium"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The electrolytic cell which is used for extraction of aluminium is a steel vessel. The vessel is lined with carbon, which acts as cathode and graphite is used at the anode.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 1)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a67417cc3fb48d668d7"},{"id":30164,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"The ore that contains the metal in the form of fluoride is known as which of the following?","question":"The ore that contains the metal in the form of fluoride is known as which of the following?","options":["cryolite","magnetite","malachite","sphalerite"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub><mo>]</mo></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>nS</mi></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a66417cc3fb48d664ad"},{"id":30081,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"<p>Which one of the following is most likely a mismatch?</p>","question":"<p>Which one of the following is most likely a mismatch?</p>","options":["<p>Zinc-Liquation</p>","<p>Copper-Electrolysis</p>","<p>Nickel-Mond process</p>","<p>Titanium-van Arkel Method</p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Mond&#39;s process involves the combination of carbon monoxide with nickel readily and reversibly and gives nickel tetracarbonyl. This process is used to extract and purify nickel.</p><p>The Van Arkel technique is used to refine Zirconium or Titanium. Impurities found in Zirconium or Titanium in the form of nitrogen and oxygen are eliminated using this technique.</p><p>Copper is purified by electrolysis. Electricity is passed through solutions containing copper compounds, such as copper sulphate. The anode (positive electrode ) is made from impure copper and the cathode (negative electrode) is made from pure copper.</p><p>Mercury and zinc are purified by distillation&nbsp;method. Liquation is a metallurgical method to remove lead containing silver from copper and remove antimony minerals from ore.</p>","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 1)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a71417cc3fb48d6867c"},{"id":30111,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"<p>In the metallurgical extraction of copper, following reaction is used :</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FeO</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>FeSiO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FeO</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeSiO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> respectively are.</p>","question":"<p>In the metallurgical extraction of copper, following reaction is used :</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FeO</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>FeSiO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FeO</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeSiO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> respectively are.</p>","options":["gangue and flux.","flux and slag","slag and flux.","Gauge and slag"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>During extraction of copper, iron oxide present as impurity is removed by adding <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and converting it into <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeSiO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FeO</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>FeSiO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Flux</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Slag</mi></math></p><p>Hence,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FeO</mi></math>&nbsp;is gangue and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeSiO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is slag.</p>","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 2)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a6e417cc3fb48d67d51"},{"id":30090,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"Which one of the following statements is incorrect ?","question":"Which one of the following statements is incorrect ?","options":["van Arkel method is used to purify tungsten.<br />&nbsp;","The malleable iron is prepared from cast iron by oxidising impurities in a reverberatory furnace.<br />&nbsp;","Cast iron is obtained by melting pig iron with scrap iron and coke using hot air blast.<br />&nbsp;","Boron and Indium can be purified by zone refining method."],"answer":0,"solution":"van Arkel method is used to purify Zirconium and Titanium.&nbsp;This method is very useful for removing all the oxygen and nitrogen present in the form of impurity in certain metals like Zr and Ti. The crude metal is heated in an evacuated vessel with iodine. The metal iodide being more covalent, volatilises:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zr</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>ZrI</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math><br />The metal iodide is decomposed on a tungsten filament, electrically heated to about <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1800</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ZrI</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Zr</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a70417cc3fb48d682f3"},{"id":30130,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"The statement that is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>INCORRECT</mi></math>&nbsp;about Ellingham diagram is","question":"The statement that is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>INCORRECT</mi></math>&nbsp;about Ellingham diagram is","options":["provides idea about the reaction rate.","provides idea about free energy change.","provides idea about changes in the phases during the reaction.","provides idea about reduction of metal oxide."],"answer":0,"solution":"Ellingham diagram is a plot between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mo>&#176;</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math> and does not give any information regarding rate of reaction","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a6b417cc3fb48d675f6"},{"id":30155,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"The major product in the following reaction is:<br /><br><img src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/pyq/jee_main/29a55f81-42ea-41d6-8422-5cbcc6cd7caf.png\" />","question":"The major product in the following reaction is:<br /><br><img src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/pyq/jee_main/29a55f81-42ea-41d6-8422-5cbcc6cd7caf.png\" />","options":["<img src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/pyq/jee_main/0a1a1087-3503-488b-9788-15fd7982ce0f.png\">","<img src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/pyq/jee_main/60f42704-5f26-47a1-9d49-7c26b06d7988.png\">","<img src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/pyq/jee_main/4ff3cac7-56c8-46b2-98b4-49cec298c19d.png\">","<img src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/pyq/jee_main/4b6b2908-df99-4458-83a5-804f7274d84f.png\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/pyq/jee_main/cc6704d0-a537-444f-b4c4-473628da387b.png\" /><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(Aromatic)</p>","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a69417cc3fb48d66d48"},{"id":30197,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"Cyanide process is used for the extraction of","question":"Cyanide process is used for the extraction of","options":["barium","aluminium","boron","silver"],"answer":3,"solution":"Forms a soluble complex which is precipitated with zinc","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a61417cc3fb48d6540c"},{"id":30193,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"During the process of electrolytic refining of copper, some metals present as impurity settle as ‘anode mud’ These are","question":"During the process of electrolytic refining of copper, some metals present as impurity settle as ‘anode mud’ These are","options":["Sn and Ag","Pb and Zn","Ag and Au","Fe and Ni"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a62417cc3fb48d6568f"},{"id":30101,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","q":"In metallurgy the term &quot;gangue&quot; is used for","question":"In metallurgy the term &quot;gangue&quot; is used for","options":["Contamination of undesired earthy materials.","Contamination of metals, other than desired metal","Minerals which are naturally occuring in pure form","Magnetic impurities in an ore."],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p style=\"display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; margin: 0px; position: absolute; top: 0px; left: -9999px; opacity: 0; overflow: hidden;\">&nbsp;</p><p>Gangue is generally an unwanted earthy material or impurity that is present in an ore. This can be found in ore deposits where the mineral is present. During the process of extraction, these impurities are mixed up with ore in the form of stone, sand, rock, etc.</p><p>The gangue must be separated from the mineral with the help of ore dressing or mineral dressing. Concentration of ore is one such process used to remove the impurities, which may depend on the physical and chemical properties. Example: Gravity separation and electromagnetic separation are some of the common methods which are used for the concentration of ore.</p><p style=\"display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; margin: 0px; position: absolute; top: 0px; left: -9999px; opacity: 0; overflow: hidden;\">&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","questionType":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null,"_marksId":"648b5a6e417cc3fb48d67da9"}]